# Set Interface: Contract, Implementations, and equals/hashCode Contract

## The Set Contract
`Set<E>` extends `Collection<E>` with one guarantee: **no duplicate elements**. Two elements `a` and `b` are duplicates if `a.equals(b)` returns `true`. The Set contract:

```java
Set<String> set = new HashSet<>();
set.add("apple");   // returns true — added
set.add("apple");   // returns false — already present, NOT added
set.size();         // 1

// This ONLY works correctly if String.equals() is implemented
// For custom objects, YOU must override equals() and hashCode()
```

## The Three Set Implementations
```java
Set<String> hashSet = new HashSet<>();       // no order, O(1) avg
Set<String> linkedSet = new LinkedHashSet<>(); // insertion order, O(1) avg
Set<String> treeSet = new TreeSet<>();       // sorted order, O(log n)
```

**HashSet:** fastest, no order guarantee. Use for deduplication and membership tests.
**LinkedHashSet:** preserves insertion order, same O(1) complexity as HashSet. Use when order matters and you need uniqueness.
**TreeSet:** elements always sorted (natural order or Comparator). Use for sorted unique elements. No null allowed (cannot compare null).

```java
// TreeSet with Comparator for custom ordering
TreeSet<Product> byPrice = new TreeSet<>(Comparator.comparing(Product::getPrice));
byPrice.add(new Product("B", 30.0));
byPrice.add(new Product("A", 10.0));
byPrice.first();  // Product("A", 10.0) — cheapest
byPrice.last();   // Product("B", 30.0) — most expensive
```

## The equals/hashCode Contract — Critical for HashSet Correctness
For a class to work correctly as Set elements, its `equals()` and `hashCode()` must satisfy:
1. **Consistency:** equal objects must have equal hash codes (if `a.equals(b)`, then `a.hashCode() == b.hashCode()`)
2. **Stability:** hash code must not change while the object is in a HashSet

```java
public class Product {
    private String id;
    private String name;

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        if (this == o) return true;
        if (!(o instanceof Product p)) return false;
        return Objects.equals(id, p.id); // equality based on id
    }

    @Override
    public int hashCode() {
        return Objects.hash(id); // MUST match equals — uses same field(s)
    }
}

Set<Product> products = new HashSet<>();
products.add(new Product("P1", "Laptop"));
products.add(new Product("P1", "Laptop Pro")); // same id → equals() returns true → NOT added
products.size(); // 1
```

## What Happens Without hashCode()
```java
public class BrokenProduct {
    private String id;
    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) { ... } // overrides equals
    // hashCode() NOT overridden — inherits Object.hashCode() which is based on identity
}

Set<BrokenProduct> set = new HashSet<>();
set.add(new BrokenProduct("P1"));
set.add(new BrokenProduct("P1")); // different object identity → different hash → different bucket → BOTH added!
set.size(); // 2 — BUG! Two logically identical products in the set
```

## Set Operations — Union, Intersection, Difference
```java
Set<String> a = new HashSet<>(Set.of("apple","banana","cherry"));
Set<String> b = new HashSet<>(Set.of("banana","cherry","date"));

// Union
Set<String> union = new HashSet<>(a); union.addAll(b);  // {apple,banana,cherry,date}

// Intersection
Set<String> intersection = new HashSet<>(a); intersection.retainAll(b); // {banana,cherry}

// Difference (a - b)
Set<String> diff = new HashSet<>(a); diff.removeAll(b);  // {apple}

// Subset check
b.containsAll(intersection); // true — intersection is a subset of b
```

## NavigableSet Methods (TreeSet)
```java
TreeSet<Integer> ts = new TreeSet<>(Set.of(1,3,5,7,9));

ts.floor(6);    // 5 — greatest element <= 6
ts.ceiling(6);  // 7 — smallest element >= 6
ts.lower(5);    // 3 — strictly less than 5
ts.higher(5);   // 7 — strictly greater than 5
ts.headSet(5);  // [1,3] — elements < 5
ts.tailSet(5);  // [5,7,9] — elements >= 5
ts.subSet(3,7); // [3,5] — elements in [3,7)
ts.pollFirst(); // removes and returns 1 (minimum)
ts.pollLast();  // removes and returns 9 (maximum)
```

## Set in Spring Boot
```java
// User roles — no duplicates, Set semantics are correct
@ManyToMany
@JoinTable(name = "user_roles")
private Set<Role> roles = new HashSet<>();

// Checking permissions
if (user.getRoles().contains(new Role("ADMIN"))) { ... }
// requires Role.equals() and hashCode() based on role name

// Deduplicating API results
Set<String> uniqueTags = articles.stream()
    .flatMap(a -> a.getTags().stream())
    .collect(Collectors.toSet()); // returns HashSet, order not guaranteed
```

## Common Mistakes
1. **Mutating a field used in hashCode() while the object is in a Set:** the object moves to the "wrong" bucket. Use immutable keys in Sets and Maps.
2. **Depending on HashSet order:** it's undefined. Use LinkedHashSet if insertion order matters, TreeSet if sorted order matters.
3. **Not implementing hashCode() when adding to HashSet:** duplicate objects appear as distinct elements.
4. **Using mutable objects as TreeSet elements without a consistent Comparator:** TreeSet relies on compare() for identity; inconsistent comparison breaks the tree.

